[Inadequate information is given in this posting to assist in understanding
the source of the enteric pathogen. To best understand this, a food
interview was likely administered to individuals who ate in the facility,
whether they became ill or not, to assess which food or foods may be suspected.
(<http://www.cdc.gov/foodborneoutbreaks/standard_questionnaire.htmis>)
Epidemic curves, from eating in the restaurant until becoming ill and cases
over time, can also be useful. The food preparers at a restaurant
represent a group that can readily contaminate food if appropriate hygienic
conditions are not maintained, but the preparers may just as well be
victims if they ingested the food vehicle as well. Although not the rule,
clusters of enteric infection have been described in which the food
vehicle (for instance, a salad bar) had been deliberately contaminated.
Except for the typhoid bacillus, all salmonellae are associated with
contact with animals or animal products such as poorly cooked chicken and
beef, uncooked eggs, and unpasteurized dairy products. Some strains are
characteristic of certain animals, such as turtles, snakes, and other
reptiles such as iguanas. The disease is usually self-limited even if
associated with fever and prominent diarrhea but can cause more significant
illnesses in immunoincompetent hosts such as patients undergoing
chemotherapy, those having received an organ transplant, or those infected
with HIV. - Mod.LL]
